# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: b-plus-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] A **B+ tree** is an m-ary tree with a variable but often large number of children per node.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] A B+ tree consists of a root, internal nodes, and leaves.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The root may be either a leaf or a node with two or more children.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] A B+ tree can be viewed as a B-tree in which each node contains only keys (not key–value pairs), and to which an additional level is added at the bottom with linked leaves.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The primary value of a B+ tree is in storing data for efficient retrieval in a block-oriented storage context—in particular, filesystems.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This is primarily because unlike binary search trees, B+ trees have very high fanout (number of pointers to child nodes in a node, typically on the order of 100 or more), which reduces the number of I/O operations required to find an element in the tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] There is no single paper introducing the B+ tree concept.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Instead, the notion of maintaining all data in leaf nodes is repeatedly brought up as an interesting variant of the B-tree, which was introduced by R.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Douglas Comer notes in an early survey of B-trees (which also covers B+ trees) that the B+ tree was used in IBM's VSAM data access software, and refers to an IBM published article from 1973.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] As with other trees, B+ trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] By definition, each value contained within the B+ tree is a key contained in exactly one leaf node.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Each key is required to be directly comparable with every other key, which forms a total order.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This enables each leaf node to keep all of its keys sorted at all times, which then enables each internal node to construct an ordered collection of intervals representing the contiguous extent of values contained in a given leaf.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Internal nodes higher in the tree can then construct their own intervals, which recursively aggregate the intervals contained in their own child internal nodes.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Eventually, the root of a B+ Tree represents the whole range of values in the tree, where every internal node represents a subinterval.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] For this recursive interval information to be retained, internal nodes must additionally contain $m-1$ copies of keys $l_{i}$ for $i\in [1,m-1]$ representing the least element within the interval covered by the child with index i (which may itself be an internal node, or a leaf).
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Where m represents the *actual* number of children for a given internal node.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The *order* or *branching factor* b of a B+ tree measures the capacity of interior nodes, i.e. their maximum allowed number of direct child nodes.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This value is constant over the entire tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] We are looking for a value k in the B+ Tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This means that starting from the root, we are looking for the leaf which may contain the value k.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] At each node, we figure out which internal node we should follow.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] An internal B+ Tree node has at most $m\leq b$ children, where every one of them represents a different sub-interval.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] We select the corresponding child via a linear search of the m entries, then when we finally get to a leaf, we do a linear search of its n elements for the desired key.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Because we only traverse one branch of all the children at each rung of the tree, we achieve $O(\log N)$ runtime, where N is the total number of keys stored in the leaves of the B+ tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Note that this pseudocode uses 1-based array indexing.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] B+ trees grow at the root and not at the leaves.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Given a collection of data records, we want to create a B+ tree index on some key field.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] One approach is to insert each record into an empty tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] However, it is quite expensive, because each entry requires us to start from the root and go down to the appropriate leaf page.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] An efficient alternative is to use bulk-loading.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The purpose of the delete algorithm is to remove the desired entry node from the tree structure.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] We recursively call the delete algorithm on the appropriate node until no node is found.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] For each function call, we traverse along, using the index to navigate until we find the node, remove it, and then work back up to the root.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Note: merge could propagate to root, which means decreasing height.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The leaves (the bottom-most index blocks) of the B+ tree are often linked to one another in a linked list; this makes range queries or an (ordered) iteration through the blocks simpler and more efficient (though the aforementioned upper bound can be achieved even without this addition).
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This does not substantially increase space consumption or maintenance on the tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] This illustrates one of the significant advantages of a B+tree over a B-tree; in a B-tree, since not all keys are present in the leaves, such an ordered linked list cannot be constructed.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] A B+tree is thus particularly useful as a database system index, where the data typically resides on disk, as it allows the B+tree to actually provide an efficient structure for housing the data itself (this is described in as index structure "Alternative 1").
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] If a storage system has a block size of B bytes, and the keys to be stored have a size of k, arguably the most efficient B+ tree is one where $b={\tfrac {B}{k}}-1$ .
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Although theoretically the one-off is unnecessary, in practice there is often a little extra space taken up by the index blocks (for example, the linked list references in the leaf blocks).
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Having an index block which is slightly larger than the storage system's actual block represents a significant performance decrease; therefore erring on the side of caution is preferable.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] If nodes of the B+ tree are organized as arrays of elements, then it may take a considerable time to insert or delete an element as half of the array will need to be shifted on average.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] To overcome this problem, elements inside a node can be organized in a binary tree or a B+ tree instead of an array.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] B+ trees can also be used for data stored in RAM.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] In this case a reasonable choice for block size would be the size of processor's cache line.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Space efficiency of B+ trees can be improved by using some compression techniques.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] One possibility is to use delta encoding to compress keys stored into each block.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] For internal blocks, space saving can be achieved by either compressing keys or pointers.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] For string keys, space can be saved by using the following technique: Normally the *i*-th entry of an internal block contains the first key of block ⁠ $i+1$ ⁠.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Instead of storing the full key, we could store the shortest prefix of the first key of block ⁠ $i+1$ ⁠ that is strictly greater (in lexicographic order) than last key of block *i*.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] There is also a simple way to compress pointers: if we suppose that some consecutive blocks ⁠ $i,i+1,...i+k$ ⁠ are stored contiguously, then it will suffice to store only a pointer to the first block and the count of consecutive blocks.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] All the above compression techniques have some drawbacks.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] First, a full block must be decompressed to extract a single element.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] One technique to overcome this problem is to divide each block into sub-blocks and compress them separately.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] In this case searching or inserting an element will only need to decompress or compress a sub-block instead of a full block.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Another drawback of compression techniques is that the number of stored elements may vary considerably from a block to another depending on how well the elements are compressed inside each block.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The ReiserFS, NSS, XFS, JFS, ReFS, and BFS filesystems all use this type of tree for metadata indexing; BFS also uses B+ trees for storing directories.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] NTFS uses B+ trees for directory and security-related metadata indexing.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] EXT4 uses extent trees (a modified B+ tree data structure) for file extent indexing.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] APFS uses B+ trees to store mappings from filesystem object IDs to their locations on disk, and to store filesystem records (including directories), though these trees' leaf nodes lack sibling pointers.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Relational database management systems such as IBM Db2, Informix, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle 8, Sybase ASE, and SQLite support this type of tree for table indices, though each such system implements the basic B+ tree structure with variations and extensions.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Many NoSQL database management systems such as CouchDB and Tokyo Cabinet also support this type of tree for data access and storage.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Finding objects in a high-dimensional database that are comparable to a particular query object is one of the most often utilized and yet expensive procedures in such systems.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] In such situations, finding the closest neighbor using a B+ tree is productive.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] B+ tree is efficiently used to construct an indexed search method called iDistance. iDistance searches for k nearest neighbors (kNN) in high-dimension metric spaces.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] The data in those high-dimension spaces is divided based on space or partition strategies, and each partition has an index value that is close with the respect to the partition.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] From here, those points can be efficiently implemented using B+ tree, thus, the queries are mapped to single dimensions ranged search.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] In other words, the iDistance technique can be viewed as a way of accelerating the sequential scan.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Instead of scanning records from the beginning to the end of the data file, the iDistance starts the scan from spots where the nearest neighbors can be obtained early with a very high probability.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Nonvolatile random-access memory (NVRAM) has been using B+ tree structure as the main memory access technique for the Internet Of Things (IoT) system because of its non static power consumption and high solidity of cell memory.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] B+ can regulate the trafficking of data to memory efficiently.
[src:b-plus-tree/b-tree] Moreover, with advanced strategies on frequencies of some highly used leaf or reference point, the B+ tree shows significant results in increasing the endurance of database systems.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] A **bitmap index** is a special kind of database index that uses bitmaps.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have traditionally been considered to work well for *low-cardinality columns*, which have a modest number of distinct values, either absolutely, or relative to the number of records that contain the data.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The extreme case of low cardinality is Boolean data (e.g., does a resident in a city have internet access?), which has two values, True and False.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes use bit arrays (commonly called bitmaps) and answer queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have a significant space and performance advantage over other structures for query of such data.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Some researchers argue that bitmap indexes are also useful for moderate or even high-cardinality data (e.g., unique-valued data) which is accessed in a read-only manner, and queries access multiple bitmap-indexed columns using the AND, OR or XOR operators extensively.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes are also useful in data warehousing applications for joining a large fact table to smaller dimension tables such as those arranged in a star schema.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] On the left, Identifier refers to the unique number assigned to each resident, HasInternet is the data to be indexed, the content of the bitmap index is shown as two columns under the heading *bitmaps*.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Each column in the left illustration under the Bitmaps header is a *bitmap* in the bitmap index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In this case, there are two such bitmaps, one for "has internet" *Yes* and one for "has internet" *No*.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] It is easy to see that each bit in bitmap *Y* shows whether a particular row refers to a person who has internet access.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This is the simplest form of bitmap index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Most columns will have more distinct values.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For example, the sales amount is likely to have a much larger number of distinct values.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Variations on the bitmap index can effectively index this data as well.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] We briefly review three such variations.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Note: Many of the references cited here are reviewed at (John Wu (2007)).
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For those who might be interested in experimenting with some of the ideas mentioned here, many of them are implemented in open source software such as FastBit, the Lemur Bitmap Index C++ Library, the Roaring Bitmap Java library and the Apache Hive Data Warehouse system.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For historical reasons, bitmap compression and inverted list compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Software can compress each bitmap in a bitmap index to save space.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] There has been considerable amount of work on this subject.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] These compression methods require very little effort to compress and decompress.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] More importantly, bitmaps compressed with BBC, WAH, COMPAX, PLWAH, EWAH and CONCISE can directly participate in bitwise operations without decompression.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This gives them considerable advantages over generic compression techniques such as LZ77.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] BBC compression and its derivatives are used in a commercial database management system.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] BBC is effective in both reducing index sizes and maintaining query performance.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] BBC encodes the bitmaps in bytes, while WAH encodes in words, better matching current CPUs.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Similar considerations can be done for CONCISE and Enhanced Word-Aligned Hybrid.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The performance of schemes such as BBC, WAH, PLWAH, EWAH, COMPAX and CONCISE is dependent on the order of the rows.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] A simple lexicographical sort can divide the index size by 9 and make indexes several times faster.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The larger the table, the more important it is to sort the rows.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Reshuffling techniques have also been proposed to achieve the same results of sorting when indexing streaming data.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Basic bitmap indexes use one bitmap for each distinct value.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] It is possible to reduce the number of bitmaps used by using a different encoding method.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For example, it is possible to encode C distinct values using log(C) bitmaps with binary encoding.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This reduces the number of bitmaps, further saving space, but to answer any query, most of the bitmaps have to be accessed.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This makes it potentially not as effective as scanning a vertical projection of the base data, also known as a materialized view or projection index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Finding the optimal encoding method that balances (arbitrary) query performance, index size and index maintenance remains a challenge.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For high-cardinality columns, it is useful to bin the values, where each bin covers multiple values and build the bitmaps to represent the values in each bin.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This approach reduces the number of bitmaps used regardless of encoding method.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] However, binned indexes can only answer some queries without examining the base data.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For example, if a bin covers the range from 0.1 to 0.2, then when the user asks for all values less than 0.15, all rows that fall in the bin are possible hits and have to be checked to verify whether they are actually less than 0.15.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The process of checking the base data is known as the candidate check.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In most cases, the time used by the candidate check is significantly longer than the time needed to work with the bitmap index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Therefore, binned indexes exhibit irregular performance.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] They can be very fast for some queries, but much slower if the query does not exactly match a bin.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The concept of bitmap index was first introduced by Professor Israel Spiegler and Rafi Maayan in their research "Storage and Retrieval Considerations of Binary Data Bases", published in 1985.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The first commercial database product to implement a bitmap index was Computer Corporation of America's Model 204.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Patrick O'Neil published a paper about this implementation in 1987.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] This implementation is a hybrid between the basic bitmap index (without compression) and the list of Row Identifiers (RID-list).
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Overall, the index is organized as a B+tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] When the column cardinality is low, each leaf node of the B-tree would contain long list of RIDs.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In this case, it requires less space to represent the RID-lists as bitmaps.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Since each bitmap represents one distinct value, this is the basic bitmap index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] As the column cardinality increases, each bitmap becomes sparse and it may take more disk space to store the bitmaps than to store the same content as RID-lists.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In this case, it switches to use the RID-lists, which makes it a B+tree index.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] One of the strongest reasons for using bitmap indexes is that the intermediate results produced from them are also bitmaps and can be efficiently reused in further operations to answer more complex queries.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Many programming languages support this as a bit array data structure.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For example, Java has the `BitSet` class and .NET have the BitArray class.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Some database systems that do not offer persistent bitmap indexes use bitmaps internally to speed up query processing.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] For example, PostgreSQL versions 8.1 and later implement a "bitmap index scan" optimization to speed up arbitrarily complex logical operations between available indexes on a single table.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] A bitmap index scan combines expressions on different indexes, thus requiring only one index per column to support all possible queries on a table.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Applying this access strategy to B-tree indexes can also combine range queries on multiple columns.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In this approach, a temporary in-memory bitmap is created with one bit for each row in the table (1 MB can thus store over 8 million entries).
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Next, the results from each index are combined into the bitmap using bitwise operations.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] After all conditions are evaluated, the bitmap contains a "1" for rows that matched the expression.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] Finally, the bitmap is traversed and matching rows are retrieved.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In addition to efficiently combining indexes, this also improves locality of reference of table accesses, because all rows are fetched sequentially from the main table.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] The internal bitmap is discarded after the query.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] If there are too many rows in the table to use 1 bit per row, a "lossy" bitmap is created instead, with a single bit per disk page.
[src:b-plus-tree/bitmap-index] In this case, the bitmap is just used to determine which pages to fetch; the filter criteria are then applied to all rows in matching pages.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The purpose of an inverted index is to allow fast full-text searches, at a cost of increased processing when a document is added to the database.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The inverted file may be the database file itself, rather than its index.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] It is the most popular data structure used in document retrieval systems, used on a large scale for example in search engines.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] Additionally, several significant general-purpose mainframe-based database management systems have used inverted list architectures, including ADABAS, DATACOM/DB, and Model 204.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] There are two main variants of inverted indexes: A **record-level inverted index** (or **inverted file index** or just **inverted file**) contains a list of references to documents for each word.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] A **word-level inverted index** (or **full inverted index** or **inverted list**) additionally contains the positions of each word within a document.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The latter form offers more functionality (like phrase searches), but needs more processing power and space to be created.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The inverted index data structure is a central component of a typical search engine indexing algorithm.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] A goal of a search engine implementation is to optimize the speed of the query: find the documents where word X occurs.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] Once a forward index is developed, which stores lists of words per document, it is next inverted to develop an inverted index.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] Querying the forward index would require sequential iteration through each document and to each word to verify a matching document.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The time, memory, and processing resources to perform such a query are not always technically realistic.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] Instead of listing the words per document in the forward index, the inverted index data structure is developed which lists the documents per word.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] With the inverted index created, the query can be resolved by jumping to the word ID (via random access) in the inverted index.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] In pre-computer times, concordances to important books were manually assembled.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] These were effectively inverted indexes with a small amount of accompanying commentary that required a tremendous amount of effort to produce.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] In bioinformatics, inverted indexes are very important in the sequence assembly of short fragments of sequenced DNA.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] One way to find the source of a fragment is to search for it against a reference DNA sequence.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] A small number of mismatches (due to differences between the sequenced DNA and reference DNA, or errors) can be accounted for by dividing the fragment into smaller fragments—at least one subfragment is likely to match the reference DNA sequence.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] The matching requires constructing an inverted index of all substrings of a certain length from the reference DNA sequence.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] Since the human DNA contains more than 3 billion base pairs, and we need to store a DNA substring for every index and a 32-bit integer for index itself, the storage requirement for such an inverted index would probably be in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:b-plus-tree/inverted-index] For historical reasons, inverted list compression and bitmap compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In computer science, the **log-structured merge-tree** (also known as **LSM tree**, or **LSMT**) is a data structure with performance characteristics that make it attractive for providing indexed access to files with high insert volume, such as transactional log data.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM trees, like other search trees, maintain key-value pairs.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM trees maintain data in two or more separate structures, each of which is optimized for its respective underlying storage medium; data is synchronized between the two structures efficiently, in batches.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] One simple version of the LSM tree is a two-level LSM tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] As described by Patrick O'Neil, a two-level LSM tree comprises two tree-like structures, called C0 and C1.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] C0 is smaller and entirely resident in memory, whereas C1 is resident on disk.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] New records are inserted into the memory-resident C0 component.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the insertion causes the C0 component to exceed a certain size threshold, a contiguous segment of entries is removed from C0 and merged into C1 on disk.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The performance characteristics of LSM trees stem from the fact that each component is tuned to the characteristics of its underlying storage medium, and that data is efficiently migrated across media in rolling batches, using an algorithm reminiscent of merge sort.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Such tuning involves writing data in a sequential manner as opposed to as a series of separate random access requests.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] This optimization reduces total seek time in hard-disk drives (HDDs) and latency in solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Most LSM trees used in practice employ multiple levels.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Level 0 is kept in main memory, and might be represented using a tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The on-disk data is organized into sorted *runs* of data.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Each run contains data sorted by the index key.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] A run can be represented on disk as a single file, or alternatively as a collection of files with non-overlapping key ranges.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] To perform a query on a particular key to get its associated value, one must search in the Level 0 tree and also each run.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The Stepped-Merge version of the LSM tree is a variant of the LSM tree that supports multiple levels with multiple tree structures at each level.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] A particular key may appear in several runs, and what that means for a query depends on the application.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Some applications simply want the newest key-value pair with a given key.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Some applications must combine the values in some way to get the proper aggregate value to return.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For example, in Apache Cassandra, each value represents a row in a database, and different versions of the row may have different sets of columns.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In order to keep down the cost of queries, the system must avoid a situation where there are too many runs.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Extensions to the 'leveled' method to incorporate B+ tree structures have been suggested, for example bLSM and Diff-Index.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] LSM-tree was originally designed for write-intensive workloads.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] As increasingly more read and write workloads co-exist under an LSM-tree storage structure, read data accesses can experience high latency and low throughput due to frequent invalidations of cached data in buffer caches by LSM-tree compaction operations.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] To re-enable effective buffer caching for fast data accesses, a Log-Structured buffered-Merged tree (LSbM-tree) is proposed and implemented.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In LSM-trees, write operations are designed to optimize performance by reducing random I/O and leveraging sequential disk writes.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] When a write operation is initiated, the data is first buffered in an in-memory component, often implemented using a sorted data structure such as a Skip list or B+ tree.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Once the in-memory buffer becomes full, it is flushed to the disk as an immutable sorted component at the first level (C1).
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] This flush is performed sequentially, ensuring high I/O efficiency by avoiding the costly random writes typical of traditional indexing methods.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] To maintain durability, the system may use a write-ahead log (WAL) that records all incoming writes before they are added to the memory buffer.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] This ensures that no data is lost in the event of a crash during a write.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] As data accumulates across levels on the disk, LSM trees employ a merge process similar to merge sort to consolidate entries and maintain a consistent sorted order across levels.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] This process also handles updates and deletes, removing redundant or obsolete entries.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Updates are treated as new writes, while deletes are marked with a tombstone entry, which is a placeholder indicating that the key has been deleted.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] These tombstones are later removed during the merging process.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Two common merging policies govern how data flows through the levels: levelling and tiering.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In levelling, only one component exists per level, and merging happens more frequently, reducing the total number of components but increasing write amplification.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In tiering, multiple components can coexist within a level, and merging occurs less frequently, reducing write amplification but increasing read costs because more components need to be searched.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] This design leads to amortized write costs of $O\left({T\cdot L \over B}\right)$ for leveling merge policies, where T is the size ratio between levels, L is the number of levels, and B is the number of entries per page.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] A point lookup operation retrieves the value associated with a specific key.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In LSM trees, because of the multi-level structure and the immutability of disk components, point lookups involve checking several levels to ensure the most up-to-date value for the key is returned.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The process begins with a search in the in-memory component (C0), which holds the latest data.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Since this component is organized as a sorted structure, the search is efficient.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the key is found here, its value is returned right away.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the key isn't found in memory, the search moves to the disk components, starting with the first level (C1) and continuing through deeper levels (C2, C3, etc.).
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Each disk level is also sorted, allowing for efficient searches using methods like binary search or tree search.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Newer levels are checked first because they contain the most recent updates and deletions for the key.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] To make the search faster, LSM trees often use a bloom filter for each on-disk component.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] These filters are probabilistic structures that help quickly determine whether a key is definitely absent from a component.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Before accessing any disk component, the system checks the Bloom filter.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the filter indicates the key is not present, the component is skipped, saving time.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the filter suggests the key might be there, the system proceeds to search for the component.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The lookup operation stops as soon as the key is found, ensuring the most recent version is returned.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] If the search reaches the final level without finding the key, the system concludes that the key doesn't exist.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Point lookup complexity is $O(L)$ without Bloom filters, as each level must be searched.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] With Bloom filters, the cost for zero-result lookups is significantly reduced to $O\left(L\cdot e^{-{\frac {M}{N}}}\right)$ , where M is the total Bloom filter size and N is the number of keys.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For existing key lookups, the cost is $O(1)$ due to the presence of Bloom filters.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] A range query retrieves all key-value pairs within a specified range.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The operation involves scanning multiple components across the LSM tree's hierarchical structure and consolidating entries to ensure accurate and complete results.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] A range query begins by searching the in-memory component (C0).
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Since this component is typically a sorted data structure, range queries can be done efficiently.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Once the in-memory component is finished, the query proceeds to the disk components, starting from the first level (C1) and continuing to deeper levels.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Each disk component is also stored as a sorted structure allowing efficient range scans within individual components.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] To perform the range query, the system locates the starting point in each relevant component and scans sequentially until the end of the range is reached.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The results from each component are then merged into a priority queue to reconcile duplicates, updates, and deletes, ensuring the final result only includes the latest version of each key.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For efficiency, LSM trees often divide disk components into smaller, disjoint key ranges.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] In this way, when processing a range query, the system can search only the partitions that have overlap ranges to reduce the number of components accessed.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] Similar to point lookup, Bloom filters are sometimes used to quickly decide whether a disk component contains any keys within the queried range, allowing the system to skip components that are guaranteed to be irrelevant.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] The performance of a range query in LSM-trees depends on the query's selectivity.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For short-range queries, which access fewer keys than twice the number of levels, the query must examine components across all levels, leading to a cost proportional to the number of levels.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For long-range queries, which access many keys, the price is dominated by scanning the largest level, as it contains most of the data.
[src:b-plus-tree/log-structured-merge-tree] For this reason, the runtime for short-range queries is $O(L)$ and $O\left({\frac {s}{B}}\right)$ for long-range queries, where s is the number of keys in the range.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial database** is a general-purpose database (usually a relational database) that has been enhanced to include spatial data that represents objects defined in a geometric space, along with tools for querying and analyzing such data.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Most spatial databases allow the representation of simple geometric objects such as points, lines and polygons.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Some spatial databases handle more complex structures such as 3D objects, topological coverages, linear networks, and triangulated irregular networks (TINs).
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] While typical databases have developed to manage various numeric and character types of data, such databases require additional functionality to process spatial data types efficiently, and developers have often added *geometry* or *feature* data types.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) developed the *Simple Features* specification (first released in 1997) and sets standards for adding spatial functionality to database systems.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The *SQL/MM Spatial* ISO/IEC standard is a part of the structured query language and multimedia standard extending the Simple Features.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The core functionality added by a spatial extension to a database is one or more *spatial datatypes*, which allow for the storage of spatial data as attribute values in a table.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Most commonly, a single spatial value would be a geometric primitive (point, line, polygon, etc.) based on the vector data model.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The datatypes in most spatial databases are based on the OGC Simple Features specification for representing geometric primitives.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Some spatial databases also support the storage of raster data.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Because all geographic locations must be specified according to a spatial reference system, spatial databases must also allow for the tracking and transformation of coordinate systems.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] In many systems, when a spatial column is defined in a table, it also includes a choice of coordinate system, chosen from a list of available systems that is stored in a lookup table.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The second major functionality extension in a spatial database is the addition of spatial capabilities to the query language (e.g., SQL); these give the spatial database the same query, analysis, and manipulation operations that are available in traditional GIS software.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] In most relational database management systems, this functionality is implemented as a set of new functions that can be used in SQL SELECT statements.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Some databases support only simplified or modified sets of these operations, especially in cases of NoSQL systems like MongoDB and CouchDB.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial index** is used by a spatial database to optimize spatial queries, implementing spatial access methods.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Database systems use indices to quickly look up values by sorting data values in a linear (e.g. alphabetical) order; however, this way of indexing data is not optimal for spatial queries in two- or three-dimensional space.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Instead, spatial databases use a *spatial* index designed specifically for multi-dimensional ordering.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] A **spatial query** is a special type of database query supported by spatial databases, including geodatabases.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The queries differ from non-spatial SQL queries in several important ways.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] Two of the most important are that they allow for the use of geometry data types such as points, lines and polygons and that these queries consider the spatial relationship between these geometries.
[src:b-plus-tree/point-access-method] The function names for queries differ across geodatabases.
